Starting with ROCm 4.0, "+code-object-v3" is no longer recognized as a valid feature-string from ADGPU targets, and result in the following warning for each HSACO codegen

```
'+code-object-v3' is not a recognized feature for this target (ignoring feature)
```

Since the hipclang compiler generates code-object-v3 objects by default now, we no longer need to the explicitly specify "+code-object-v3" as a feature-string. license to the header but that wasn't detected until the PR was improted
internally.

[{"sha":"f4dc69a5b83b96f3b4a0a080f3830a16d6b260cd","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update the style checks to also include the reference kernels.

Prior to this change we were only looking at code within the
tensorflow/lite/micro directory. However, TFLM does share the reference
implementations with Lite and so we are also checking for license and
formatting in those files.

This should help detect errors faster, for example, PR

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

information, as provisioners should not be logging connection

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"},{"sha":"d380f5873c5ba09b99860fba061200a6e27b3aaa","author":{"name":"Paul Thrasher","email":"d943e3484fefc8c5080ef9d8c0757459e55f3371@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Allow runs to continue on tfce error

* feat(kuma-cp) send custom strings in health checks

Introducing new field called `tcp` in HealthCheck resource, with
fields `send` and `receive`, which can be provided and will configure
envoy to send provided bytes during tcp health check and expecting
provided bytes in response. Field `receive` expect list of bytes as you
can specify multiple byte blocks. When checking the response,
“fuzzy” matching is performed such that each block must be found, and in
the order specified, but not necessarily contiguous.

More:
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/upstream/cluster_manager/cluster_hc#config-cluster-manager-cluster-hc

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* feat(kuma-cp) http health checks

Introduced possibility to provide HTTP configuration for health checks,
which will send health checks as HTTP requests.

As internal traffic is mostly using HTTP 2, it's the default protocol
used when health checks are configured to use HTTP. To change that
behaviour you can use `http.use_http1` parameter and set it to true.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) regenerate protobufs for healthchecks

As in master landed PR with protobuf upgrade, I had to regenerate
protbuf related code for health checks, it also involved small changes
in health_check_configurer_test.go file.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) adress comments from CR + more

- Found nasty bug when provided `expectedStatuses` in your health check
  manifest it was generating wrong Int64Range as it should be half
  closed (`start` is inclusive and `end` is exclusive), so it was fixed,
  and the tests reflects this
- Changed some of the properties of the HealthCheck resource to the
  primitive ones (`string`s) and removed logic related to validation if
  the value is provided or empty
- As after protobuf upgrade when unmarshaling our manifests when
  provided empty slices they are becoming `nil`s
- Used `oneof` for `http`/`tcp` blocks in HealthCheck resource and
  removed validation logic which was checking if both of them were not
  provided at the same time

* feat(*) retry policy

* chore(*) make check update

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* fix(kuma-cp) fix grpc retryOn values

When providing retryOn values in grpc Retry configuration, you have to
use values with underscores (`_`) instead of hyphens (`-`) but envoy
expects the later ones, so we have to replace all underscores with
hyphens. It was missing before

  policies to work in kubernetes
- Added additional tests for Retry topology

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) update to v2/v3 listeners/routes

It's a result of rebasing after introducing:
https://github.com/kumahq/kuma/pull/1323

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* chore(*) run make check

* chore(*) make check update

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

* fix(kuma-cp) retryOn value case fix

As it occured during our live tests if the value is set to upper case -
`5XX` it's comming through envoy validation but it's not working as
expected, so changing the case to `5xx` fixes this.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

the backOff properties

[{"sha":"619c6727ef5bfb3c3c6cd056aafe9dc0b7f484a7","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"backend/remote: No version check for operations

Terraform remote version conflicts are not a concern for operations. We
are in one of three states:

- Running remotely, in which case the local version is irrelevant;
- Workspace configured for local operations, in which case the remote
  version is meaningless;
- Forcing local operations with a remote backend, which should only
  happen in the Terraform Cloud worker, in which case the Terraform
  versions by definition match.

This commit therefore disables the version check for operations (plan
and apply), which has the consequence of disabling it in Terraform Cloud

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"},{"sha":"d380f5873c5ba09b99860fba061200a6e27b3aaa","author":{"name":"Paul Thrasher","email":"d943e3484fefc8c5080ef9d8c0757459e55f3371@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Allow runs to continue on tfce error

technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.

[{"sha":"619c6727ef5bfb3c3c6cd056aafe9dc0b7f484a7","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"backend/remote: No version check for operations

Terraform remote version conflicts are not a concern for operations. We
are in one of three states:

- Running remotely, in which case the local version is irrelevant;
- Workspace configured for local operations, in which case the remote
  version is meaningless;
- Forcing local operations with a remote backend, which should only
  happen in the Terraform Cloud worker, in which case the Terraform
  versions by definition match.

This commit therefore disables the version check for operations (plan
and apply), which has the consequence of disabling it in Terraform Cloud
and Enterprise runs. In turn this enables Terraform Enterprise runs with
bundles which have a version that doesn't exactly match the bundled
Terraform version.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/619c6727ef5bfb3c3c6cd056aafe9dc0b7f484a7"},{"sha":"577b1ea2afc07409f41844b9eb5becc9897b38f0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"core: Fix for sensitive data source arguments","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/terraform/commits/577b1ea2afc07409f41844b9eb5becc9897b38f0"},{"sha":"3ce7edc0183fac7c6bca40cbe9fe2bd0554f8382","author":{"name":"stakiran","email":"494a45ad7244a76f9ef40dbfddd762a8af24e370@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Fix wrong link of operators.

[{"sha":"fbc41456a890a2f4a990420e32e8cca71d9c025e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

In prior versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened
during `terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove
missing resources from state as required. Because the destroy plan only
creates the necessary changes for apply to remove all the resources, it
does no reading of resources or data sources, leading to state data in
the state. In most cases this is not a problem, but when a provider
configuration is using resource values, the provider may not be able to
run correctly during apply.

Because the destroy plan graph is so minimal, it is not feasible to work
the reading of resources into the operation without completely
replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan graph and all
destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount of
refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to refresh
the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back similar
behavior to version prior to 0.14, and can also be skipped using the
`-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/fbc41456a890a2f4a990420e32e8cca71d9c025e"},{"sha":"b923bb1f38693fe67234019f8f306a0b82e1c387","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not
expect the resources to be read.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b923bb1f38693fe67234019f8f306a0b82e1c387"}]

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

default), however the output is intended to be viewed in the UI by the
user, rather than in a separate stream. Terraform also generally does
not consider warnings to be errors from the cli point of view, and does
not need to output the warning text to stderr.

The resources, expressions, and modules pages were all split into smaller, more
navigable pages, but the old URLs had accumulated a large number of deep links
to their section headers. To help people recover when they click an old link, we
converted those old URLs to landing pages, which preserve all of the old in-page
anchors and point readers to the appropriate new destinations.

However, because the new link-to-new-page sections are so small, it was kind of
hard to tell which section you had clicked into! Especially if you were near the
bottom of the page and the browser wasn't able to position the desired section
at the very top of the window.

This commit aims to improve that by putting one full screen of whitespace in
between every linkable section on these landing pages. Yes, it's a hack, but
you're meant to only view these pages for three seconds or so before moving on
to the place you wanted to be, and this should help dispel any confusion about
which place that is.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vsimon/terraform/commits/83ebb9b17898b114465f88fd4a1e2a8eaffb34d6"}]

[{"sha":"dfd903e187d04e628f875a35fc7b7a33dc945590","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh state during a destroy plan

Because the destroy plan only creates the necessary changes for apply to
remove all the resources, it does no reading of resources or data
sources, leading to stale data in the state. In most cases this is not a
problem, but when a provider configuration is using resource values, the
provider may not be able to run correctly during apply. In prior
versions of terraform, the implicit refresh that happened during
`terraform destroy` would update the data sources and remove missing
resources from state as required.

The destroy plan graph has a minimal amount of information, so it is not
feasible to work the reading of resources into the operation without
completely replicating the normal plan graph, and updating the plan
graph and all destroy node implementation is also a considerable amount
of refactoring. Instead, we can run a normal plan which is used to
refresh the state before creating the destroy plan. This brings back
similar behavior to core versions prior to 0.14, and the refresh can
still be skipped using the `-refresh=false` cli flag.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/dfd903e187d04e628f875a35fc7b7a33dc945590"},{"sha":"325fec2e1a315581ec5e0a721d8115b86b917b7e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"refresh is expected for destroy

These tests were not previously running a refresh, and hence did not
expect the resources to be read.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/325fec2e1a315581ec5e0a721d8115b86b917b7e"}]

[{"sha":"b4ec23184211abbe9d084312b2b305ffc3ddfa75","author":{"name":"Andrew Or","email":"a5c478d606458f6c868a5126471748acd4730a6f@gmail.com"},"message":"Sum, not average, local losses (gradients) for HT

HT = heterogeneous training

We do this because averaging local losses would lead to incorrect
gradients. E.g. suppose we have 2 GPUs and a global batch size of
64. GPU X is assigned 48 examples while GPU Y is assigned 16
examples. If we average local losses, which is the default, we
will end up with:

((X / 48) + (Y / 16)) / 2 = (X + 3Y) / 96

But what we want is:

(X + Y) / 64

which would match the semantics of running the same batch in a
non-heterogeneous setting. Therefore, we need to sum the losses
(X + Y) and divide by the global batch size (64) instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/andrewor14/tensorflow/commits/b4ec23184211abbe9d084312b2b305ffc3ddfa75"}]
